column168: 1/26/87 - 1515 HRS. KURZANSKI WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT BY CHIEF DISPATC HER - D BEATY (CHGO) KURZANSKI CONTACTED PAT TAPRICK TERM. MGR. - BULK INTE RMODAL DISTRIBUTION SERCIVE (CSX-BIDS) BY PHONE AT 1520 HRS. INFOR FROM PAT RICK AS FOLLOWS: AT APPROX. 1400 HRS. TENNYBROOK TRANS. CO. TRUCK T-14 WITH TANK #5741 BEGAN TO LOAD IT'S LADING, FERROUS CHLORIDE (UN 1760) INTO TANK CAR GATX 27321 ON TRK #6 WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE TANK TRUCK WAS L EAKING FROM A POSSIBLE CRACK IN THE BOTTOM (A FAST DRIP). PATRICK AND THE D RIVER PUT ABSORBENT PADS AND A BUCKET UNDERNEATH THE TANK TRUCK AND CONTINU ED TO OFF LOAD IT. AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HRS. THE LEAK STOPPED, AS PRESSURE IN THE TANK DROPPED. THE TANK WAS COMPLETELY OFF LOADED AT APPROX. 1600 HR S. TENNYBROOK REPRESENTATIVES REMOVED THE PADS, BUCKET, ETC. FROM THE SCENE . PATRICK STATED THAT THEY WOULD APPLY LIME TO THE SPILL THE NEXT MORNING. DRIVER ESTIMATED A SPILL OF 100 GALS. KURZANSKI RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AT 1 615 HRS. AND MET WITH PATRICK. THERE WERE TWO SPILLS, BOTH SOAKED INTO THE BALLAST (1-10'X4', 1-4' X3'). PATRICK NOTIFIED KURZANSKI ON 1/27/87 AT 930 HRS. TNAT TENNYBROOK HAD APPLIED LIME TO THE SPILL AREA AND CLEANED SAME UP AT 0830 HRS 1/27/87.
